   },
   "source": [
    "<span style=\"color:red\">**Question:** </span> Show the probabilistic view of the data. Assume that the data is drawn from a 2D distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.stats import multivariate_normal\n",
    "\n",
    "mu = np.mean(iris_df_new.values,0)\n",
    "Sigma = np.cov(iris_df_new.values.transpose())\n",
    "\n",
    "min_length = np.min(iris_df_new.values[:,0]);\n",
    "min_width = np.min(iris_df_new.values[:,1]);\n",
    "max_length = np.max(iris_df_new.values[:,0]);\n",
    "max_width = np.max(iris_df_new.values[:,1]);\n",
    "x, y = np.mgrid[min_length:max_length:50j, min_width:max_width:50j]\n",
    "\n",
    "positions = np.empty(x.shape + (2,))\n",
    "positions[:, :, 0] = x; \n",
    "positions[:, :, 1] = y\n",
    "\n",
    "F = multivariate_normal(mu, Sigma)\n",
    "Z = F.pdf(positions)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,

   "source": [
    "def mycov(data, col_a, col_b):\n",
    "    mu = np.mean(data, axis=0) #compute mean\n",
    "    sum = 0;\n",
    "    for i in range(0, len(data)):\n",
    "        sum += ((data[i,col_a] - mu[col_a]) * (data[i,col_b] - mu[col_b]))\n",
    "\n",
    "    return sum/(len(data)-1)"
   ]

   "source": [
    "### 5. Dimensionality Reduction: PCA\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "<span style=\"color:red\">**Question:** </span>\n",
    "Project points in the digits dataset onto a two-dimensional space using PCA. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "Steps involved in PCA\n",
    "1. Input data: set of points in $R^d$\n",
    "2. Compute covariance matrix $\\Sigma$ (a $d \\times d$ matrix)\n",
    "3. Compute Eigenvectors of $\\Sigma$\n",
    "4. Select $r$ Eigenvectors (based on a parameter or based on variance explained) corresponding to the highest eigenvalues\n",

   "source": [
    "### 7. Linear Discriminant Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "We will use iris data to study LDA. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 54,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X = iris_df.values[:,0:4]\n",
    "y = iris_df.values[:,4] "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "We will use the first 100 samples. The first 50 are of the class 'Iris-setosa' and the rest are of the class 'Iris-versicolor'."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 55,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X = X[0:100,:]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 56,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X = X.astype(float)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 57,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],

    "y = y[0:100]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "<span style=\"color:red\">**Question:** </span>\n",
    "Plot the heatpmap of the data. And determine which attributes can be used for projection so the two classes are well separated. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 58,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {

    }
   },
   "outputs": [

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "<span style=\"color:green\">Answer: </span> \n",
    "\n",
    "The last two attributes are useful to separate the two classes. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "<span style=\"color:red\">**Question:** </span>\n",
    "Using only the first two attributes, project the selected points in X (below) from the iris dataset using LDA. Determine if the two classes are separated despite choosing the first two attributes. Compute the absolute difference between the two means in the projected space. \n",
    "Hint: Use LinearDiscriminantAnalysis function from scikit library. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "**Steps involved in performing LDA**\n",
    "1. Input data: set of points in $R^d$\n",
    "2. Compute mean vectors $\\mu_1$ and $\\mu_2$\n",
    "3. Compute between class scatter matrix $S_B$\n",
    "4. Compute within class scatter matrix $S_W$\n",
    "5. Compute the matrix $S_W^{-1}S_B$\n",
    "4. Compute the first eigenvector ($v_1$) of the matrix $S_W^{-1}S_B$\n",
    "5. Project data on to this eigenvector $Xv_1$\n",
    "\n",
    "LinearDiscriminantAnalysis function accomplishes all of this."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 59,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "lda = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis(n_components=2)\n",
    "X_r1 = lda.fit(X[:,0:2], y).transform(X[:,0:2])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 60,
